data.content:
MSTest has a dedicated `CollectionAssert` class and better assertion methods. Your current approach using `Assert.IsTrue` gives poor failure messages (just "expected true, got false"). Here's the improved version:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void GetActiveUsers_ReturnsOnlyActiveUsers()
{
    var service = new UserService();
    var users = service.GetActiveUsers();

    // Use AreEqual for exact counts — shows expected vs actual on failure
    Assert.AreEqual(3, users.Count);

    // CollectionAssert for collection-specific checks
    CollectionAssert.AllItemsAreNotNull(users);

    // Assert.IsTrue is fine for predicate checks, but use a message
    Assert.IsTrue(users.All(u => u.IsActive), "Expected all users to be active");

    // Use IsNotNull instead of Assert.IsTrue(x != null)
    var admin = users.Single(u => u.Role == "Admin");
    Assert.IsNotNull(admin);
}
```

**Key improvements:**

| Instead of | Use | Why |
|---|---|---|
| `Assert.IsTrue(x.Count > 0)` | `Assert.AreEqual(3, count)` or `CollectionAssert.That` | Shows actual vs expected |
| `Assert.IsTrue(x != null)` | `Assert.IsNotNull(x)` | Clearer failure message |
| `Assert.IsTrue(condition)` | Add a `message` parameter | Explains *what* failed |

**Other useful `CollectionAssert` methods:**

```csharp
CollectionAssert.Contains(users, expectedUser);
CollectionAssert.DoesNotContain(users, bannedUser);
CollectionAssert.AreEqual(expected, actual);        // same order
CollectionAssert.AreEquivalent(expected, actual);   // any order
CollectionAssert.IsSubsetOf(subset, superset);
CollectionAssert.AllItemsAreUnique(users);
```

The general rule: prefer the most specific assertion available — it produces the most helpful failure messages.
